package zeroclaw:plugin@0.1.0;

/// Host-mediated outbound raw TCP (+TLS) client for channel plugins whose
/// platform speaks a raw byte protocol over a socket (IRC, IMAP/SMTP email,
/// MQTT, AMQP).
///
/// A channel plugin runs in a WASI sandbox with no network and no sockets, so
/// it cannot open a TCP connection itself. Exactly as the host runs a plugin's
/// inbound listener and performs its `wasi:http` TLS, the host owns the socket
/// here: it resolves and dials `host:port`, optionally performs the TLS client
/// handshake (`tls = true`), and pumps bytes, exposing each live connection to
/// the plugin as an opaque `u64` handle. The plugin drives the application
/// protocol — it queues outbound byte chunks and drains received ones — while
/// the host stays protocol-agnostic. The host performs no app-level protocol
/// work (IRC registration, IMAP login, MQTT keepalive); that all stays in the
/// plugin, which owns the platform's framing and timing.
///
/// Gated by the `socket_client` permission: a plugin without it never gets a
/// connection registry, the import is not linked, and a guest that imports this
/// interface fails closed at instantiation.
///
/// The feature annotation lives on the `channel-plugin` world import. Keeping
/// this definition visible avoids a `wit-parser` feature-remapping failure when
/// another transport feature is enabled without sockets.
interface socket {
    /// One event drained from a live connection by `tcp-receive`.
    variant socket-event {
        /// A chunk of received bytes. Raw TCP has no framing: chunk boundaries
        /// are arbitrary, and the plugin must reassemble its own protocol units.
        data(list<u8>),
        /// No bytes were ready. The plugin should back off and poll again,
        /// exactly as it backs off on an empty `inbound-poll`.
        idle,
        /// The connection closed (peer close, read/write error, or stream end);
        /// the string is a human-readable reason. Returning this event retires
        /// the handle and releases its host connection slot — the plugin must
        /// `tcp-connect` again to reconnect. Any bytes buffered before the close
        /// are still delivered first.
        closed(string),
    }

    /// Open a TCP connection to `host:port`. The `socket_client` capability is
    /// public-network-only: local/private names are rejected, DNS is resolved
    /// once, and every resolved address must be globally routable before the
    /// host dials that checked address set. There is no private-network
    /// exception. A destination rejection starts with the stable error key
    /// `socket_destination_not_allowed`.
    ///
    /// When `tls` is true the host performs a TLS client handshake (SNI from
    /// `host`, WebPKI roots) over the socket before returning and needs no
    /// plaintext exception. When `tls` is false, the exact host must be allowed
    /// by the operator's live
    /// `plugins.security.socket_plaintext_allowed_hosts` policy; absent an
    /// exact match, the call fails closed with the stable error key
    /// `socket_plaintext_not_allowed`. Plaintext authorization never overrides
    /// the public-network-only destination guard. Returns an opaque connection
    /// handle on success, or an error string when policy, resolve, dial, or
    /// handshake fails.
    tcp-connect: func(host: string, port: u16, tls: bool) -> result<u64, string>;

    /// Queue a chunk of bytes to send on the connection. Each call is bounded
    /// by a host-defined maximum chunk size before the bytes can enter the
    /// outbound queue; an oversized chunk fails with the stable error key
    /// `socket_outbound_chunk_too_large` and is not retained. Also errors if the
    /// handle is unknown or the outbound buffer is full; a full buffer signals
    /// the plugin is producing faster than the socket drains.
    tcp-send: func(handle: u64, bytes: list<u8>) -> result<_, string>;

    /// Drain the next event from the connection without blocking. Returns
    /// `idle` immediately when no bytes are queued, or `closed` once the
    /// connection has ended and its buffered chunks are exhausted. A terminal
    /// `closed` event consumes the handle and releases its connection slot;
    /// subsequent calls with that handle report it as unknown. Errors only if
    /// the handle is unknown.
    tcp-receive: func(handle: u64) -> result<socket-event, string>;

    /// Number of byte chunks currently buffered for the connection, so the
    /// plugin can drain in batches without a sentinel `idle` between each.
    /// Errors if the handle is unknown.
    tcp-pending: func(handle: u64) -> result<u32, string>;

    /// Close the connection and release the handle, aborting its host pump
    /// tasks. Idempotent: closing an already-closed or unknown handle is a
    /// no-op.
    tcp-close: func(handle: u64);
}
